        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Ecc&egrave; heroicum facinus Horatij Coclitis, egregij et vnici viri.
                        Multum valet unum terribile, et admirabile opus in extremo periculo: et sit Cocles viuidum, feruidumq[ue] exemplum cuiq[ue] cordato viro. 
                        Quicquid vno corpore pra[e]stari potest vllo impetu, id extendatur animosissim&egrave;.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Horatius Cocles"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="extremo periculo:"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>See the heroic deed of Horatius Cocles, an outstanding and singular man!
                In extreme danger one frightful and remarkable work is of great value, and let Cocles be a lively, fierce example for any sensible man. 
                Whatever one can accomplish with one single body in any attack, let it be stretched out in the boldest way.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>"Vnum tale facinus egregium, quale Bruti, Coclitis, Sca[e]uola[e], Coriolani, Cla[e]lia[e], Agrippa[e] 
                        "in isto libro; hominem domi, forisq[ue] nobilitat; eumq[ue] facit, si in Liuium incidat historicum, immortalem. 
                        "At nihil tale feci; diceret h&icirc;c iuuenis Ca[e]sar, etiam cum lacrymis: protinusq[ue] aliquid ingentius perpetraret; 
                        "et acerrim&egrave; talis esse contenderet, qualis videri cuperet. Cert&egrave; Vnica vera[e] gloria[e] via, seria solidaq[ue] 
                        virtus; pra[e]culta efficaci Arte: Et Famam extendere Factis, Hoc Virtutis opus; ait Romanorum poetarum prudentissimus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Lucius Junius Brutus"/>
                    <person name="Horatius Cocles"/>
                    <person name="Gaius Mucius Scaevola"/> <!--It's likely that Harvey means this Scaevola, whom he's mentioned before-->
                    <person name="Marcius Coriolanus"/>
                    <person name="Claelia"/>
                    <person name="Menenius Agrippa Lanatus"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Caesar"/>
                    <X-ref person="Virgil" book_title="Aeneid" language="LA" text="Et famam extendere factis, hoc virtutis opus"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Vnum tale facinus egregium"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>One such excellent deed of the kind as that of Brutus, Cocles, Scaevola, Coriolanus, Claelia, Agrippa in this book, makes a man renowned
                at home and abroad. And if it happens to come to the attention of the historian Livy, it makes him immortal. “But I have done nothing of such a kind,” 
                a young Caesar would say, in tears even, and immediately he would achieve something really great, exerting himself in the most vigorous way to be such as he wanted to appear. 
                This is certainly an unparalleled path to true honour, and it is an earnest, strong virtue developed beforehand through effective craft. 
                “Yet to increase fame through deeds, that is the work of virtue”, says the most sagacious of the Roman poets.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
